5–Deceased","1196–Male":"1196–Deceased","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1130–Female":"1130–Deceased","ABT 1185":"about 1185","about 1160":"about 1160","ABT 1197":"about 1197","1157":"1157","1196":"1196","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1020":"1020","1160":"1160","Tregynon, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Tregynon, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomery,Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Tregynon, Montgomery, Wales":"Tregynon, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Meilir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Plum jade’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gryg","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Gregory   and   Gregor ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gregg","meanings":["Short form of   Gregory   and   Gregor ."]},{"name":"Gregory","meanings":["Via Latin <i>Gregorius</i> from the post-classical Greek name <i>Gregōrios</i> ‘watchful’ (a derivative of <i>gregōrein</i> ‘to watch, be vigilant’). The name was a very popular one among the early Christians, who were mindful of the injunction ‘be sober, be vigilant’ (1 Peter 5:8). It was borne by a number of early saints. The most important, in honour of whom the name was often bestowed from medieval times onwards, were Gregory of Nazianzen (  <i>c.</i>329–90 ), Gregory of Nyssa (  d. <i>c.</i>395 ), Gregory of Tours (  538–94 ), and  Pope Gregory the Great  (  <i>c.</i>540–604 ). A famous bearer of the name in modern times is the film star  Gregory Peck  (  1916–2003 ). The name has traditionally been popular in Scotland, where it is often found in the form  <b>Gregor</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Meilir Gryg ap Gruffudd was born about 1160, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, his father, Gruffudd ap Iorwerth, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Gruffudd ap Iorwerth, was 32. He married Dyddgu 'Jane' verch Rotpert of Cedewain about 1197, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in Tregynon, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1160–":"umbes 1160–Surnud","1020–Male":"1020–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1157–Female":"1157–Surnud","1185–Female":"11